      • addInt

        public CallParams<Kind> addInt(long value,
                               int width)
        Add an integer as an signed intN param, explicitly setting the parameter width.

        The value will be truncated to the last width bits, the same as Java's behavior when casting from a larger integer type to a smaller one. When passing a smaller integer type, Java will widen it by sign-extending so if it is truncated again it should still result in the same two's complement value.

        Parameters:
        width - the nominal bit width for encoding the integer type in the function selector, e.g. width = 128 produces a param type of int128; must be a multiple of 8 and between 8 and 256.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if width is not in a valid range (see above).

      • addInt

        public CallParams<Kind> addInt(BigInteger bigInt,
                               int width)
        Add an arbitrary precision integer as a signed intN param, explicitly setting the parameter width.
        Parameters:
        width - the nominal bit width for encoding the integer type in the function selector, e.g. width = 128 produces a param type of int128; must be a multiple of 8 and between 8 and 256.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if bigInt.bitLength() > 255 (max range including the sign bit), width < uint.bitLength() or width is not in a valid range (see above).

      • addIntArray

        public CallParams<Kind> addIntArray(long[] intArray,
                                    int intWidth,
                                    int fixedLen)
        Add a fixed-length integer array as a signed intM[N] param, explicitly setting the integer bit-width and array length.

        The values will be truncated to the last width bits, the same as Java's behavior when casting from a larger integer type to a smaller one. When passing a smaller integer type, Java will widen it by sign-extending so if it is truncated again it should still result in the same two's complement value.

        Parameters:
        intWidth - the nominal bit width for encoding the integer type in the function selector, e.g. width = 128 produces a param type of int128; must be a multiple of 8 and between 8 and 256.
        fixedLen - the nominal length of the fixed-size array; must be the length of the array that is passed.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if width is not in a valid range (see above) or fixedLen != intArray.length.

      • addUint

        public CallParams<Kind> addUint(@Nonnegative
                                long uint,
                                int width)
        Add a non-negative integer as an unsigned uintN param, explicitly setting the parameter width.

        The value will be truncated to the last width bits, the same as Java's behavior when casting from a larger integer type to a smaller one. Passing a smaller integer type is allowed.

        Parameters:
        width - the nominal bit width for encoding the integer type in the function selector, e.g. width = 128 produces a param type of uint128; must be a multiple of 8 and between 8 and 256.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if uint < 0, or width is not in a valid range (see above).

      • addUint

        public CallParams<Kind> addUint(@Nonnegative
                                BigInteger uint,
                                int width)
        Add an arbitrary precision non-negative integer as an unsigned uintN param, explicitly setting the parameter width.

        As this uses the unsigned type, it gets an extra bit of range over addInt(BigInteger, int) which has to count the sign bit.

        Parameters:
        width - the nominal bit width for encoding the integer type in the function selector, e.g. width = 128 produces a param type of uint128; must be a multiple of 8 and between 8 and 256.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if uint.signum() < 0, if uint.bitLength() > 256 (cannot be represented as a Solidity integer type), width < uint.bitLength() or width is not in a valid range (see above).

      • addUintArray

        public CallParams<Kind> addUintArray(long[] uintArray,
                                     int intWidth)
        Add an array of non-negative integers as an unsigned intN[] param, explicitly setting the integer bit-width.

        The values will be truncated to the last width bits, the same as Java's behavior when casting from a larger integer type to a smaller one. When passing a smaller integer type, Java will widen it by sign-extending so if it is truncated again it should still result in the same two's complement value.

        Parameters:
        intWidth - the nominal bit width for encoding the integer type in the function selector, e.g. width = 128 produces a param type of int128; must be a multiple of 8 and between 8 and 256.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if any value is less than 0, width is not in a valid range (see above), or fixedLen != intArray.length.
